{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20180905220511|858241762","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Lou_Barletta","to":"Lou Barletta"}],"pages":{"16201960":{"pageid":16201960,"ns":0,"title":"Lou Barletta","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2018-09-22T03:02:39Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{POV|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Lou Barletta\n|image        = Lou Barletta.jpg\n|state        = [[Pennsylvania]]\n|district     = {{ushr|PA|11|11th}}\n|term_start   = January 3, 2011\n|term_end     =\n|predecessor  = [[Paul Kanjorski]]\n|successor    =\n|office1      = [[Mayoralty in the United States|Mayor]] of [[Hazleton, Pennsylvania|Hazleton]]\n|term_start1  = January 3, 1999\n|term_end1    = December 14, 2010\n|predecessor1 = Mike Marsicano\n|successor1   = Joseph Yannuzzi\n|birth_name   = Louis James Barletta\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1956|1|28}}\n|birth_place  = [[Hazleton, Pennsylvania|Hazleton]], [[Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n|death_date   =\n|death_place  =\n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse       = Mary Malloy\n|children     = 4 daughters\n|education    = [[Luzerne County Community College]]<br>[[Bloomsburg University of Pennsylvania|Bloomsburg University]]\n}}\n'''Louis James Barletta''' (born January 28, 1956) is an American politician and businessman serving as the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|PA|11}} since 2011. A member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], he previously served as Mayor of [[Hazleton, Pennsylvania]] from 1999 to 2010. As Mayor, he came to prominence due to a high-profile anti-immigration ordinance that spurred legal challenges and was later found unconstitutional.<ref name=\":4\" /> The legal fees related to defending the ordinance contributed to making the city financially distressed, and it no longer enforces the ordinance.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nBarletta is the Republican nominee in the [[United States Senate election in Pennsylvania, 2018|2018 U.S. Senate election in Pennsylvania]].\n\n==Early life, education, and business career==\nBarletta was born January 28, 1956 in Hazleton, Pennsylvania, the son of Angeline (n\u00e9e Agosti) and Rocco Barletta, both of Italian ancestry.<ref name=CQ>{{cite news |title=112th Congress: Lou Barletta, R-Pa. (11th District) |first=Anna |last=Palmer |newspaper=[[Congressional Quarterly]] |date=November 3, 2010 |url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/cq/20101103/pl_cq_politics/politics000003758207_3 |accessdate=}}</ref>  After graduating from high school, he attended [[Luzerne County Community College]] and [[Bloomsburg University of Pennsylvania]].  After an unsuccessful tryout for the [[Cincinnati Reds]] baseball team,<ref name=Enough>{{cite news |author=Vanessa Gezari |title=Hazelton mayor says enough, already! |url= http://www.sptimes.com/2006/07/02/Worldandnation/Hazelton_mayor_says_e.shtml |work=St. Petersburg Times |date=2006-07-02 |accessdate=2008-11-01}}</ref> Barletta went to work for his family's construction and heating oil business.\n\nIn 1984, Barletta founded a pavement marking company, Interstate Road Marking Corporation, which he sold in 2000. At the time of the sale, his firm had grown to become the largest of its kind in Pennsylvania.\n\n==Mayor of Hazleton==\nHe was defeated for a seat on the Hazleton City Council in 1996, but won two years later. In 1999, he defeated Jack Mundie for mayor, taking 66% of the vote<ref name=Elected>{{cite news |author=Andrew Tutino |title=Barletta Elected Hazelton Mayor |work=Wilkes Barre Times Leader |date=1999-11-03}}</ref> and overcoming a Democratic registration edge in the city.<ref name=Beyond>{{cite news |author=Bill O'Boyle |title=Beyond the city limits |work=Wilkes Barre Times Leader |date=2007-11-11 }}</ref> He took office on January 3, 1999.<ref>{{cite news |title=Councilmen Skeptical of Candidates |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=WB&s_site=timesleader&p_multi=WB&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB71A947A7174C6&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |date=2000-01-02 |accessdate=2011-01-04}}</ref>\n\nBarletta was reelected as mayor in 2003 and 2007.  In 2007, Barletta was nominated in both the Republican and Democratic primary elections. Barletta defeated the Democratic candidate, former Mayor Michael Marsicano, on the Democratic ballot as a write-in.<ref name=Foe>{{cite news |author=Michael Rubincam |title=Mayor Who Targeted Illegals Wins _ Twice |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/n/a/2007/05/15/national/a232225D09.DTL&type=politics |work=Associated Press, Printed in the San Francisco Chronicle |date=2007-05-15 |accessdate=2008-11-01}}</ref>\n\n===Immigration ordinance, lawsuit and financial distress===\nIn 2006, Barletta made headlines for his efforts opposing illegal immigration in Hazleton vowing to make the city \"one of the toughest places in the United States\" for illegal immigrants.<ref name=\"Void\">{{cite news |author=Julia Preston |title=Judge Voids Ordinance on Illegal Immigrants |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/07/27/us/27hazelton.html |work=New York Times |date=2007-07-27 |accessdate=2008-11-01}}</ref> Barletta introduced and the city council approved the Illegal Immigration Relief Act.<ref>http://thehill.com/capital-living/new-member-of-the-week/167251-barletta-makes-pitch-on-immigration</ref> The ordinance allowed the city to deny a business permit to employers who hired illegal immigrants and gave the city authority to fine landlords up to $1,000 for leasing to illegal immigrants.<ref name=\"Void\" /><ref name=\"Court\">{{cite news |author=Dwayne Parker |title=Hazleton Immigration Laws Head to Court |url=http://wfmz.com/view/?id=567942 |work=69 News |date=2008-10-30 |accessdate=2008-11-01}}</ref> The act also made English the official language of Hazleton, prohibiting city employees from translating documents into any language without official authorization.<ref name=\"Notice\">{{cite news |author=Michael Powell and Michelle Garc\u00eda |title=Pa. City Puts Illegal Immigrants on Notice |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/08/21/AR2006082101484.html |work=Washington Post |date=2006-08-22 |accessdate=2008-11-01}}</ref> In response, the [[ACLU]] and [[Puerto Rican Legal Defense and Education Fund]] sued in [[United States district court|Federal District Court]] to block the ordinance.<ref name=\"Notice\" /> \n\nIn July 2007, District Court Judge James M. Munley ruled that the act was unconstitutional for interfering with Federal immigration laws and violating the due process of individuals, employers and landlords.<ref name=\"Void\" /> The ruling was upheld on appeal to the [[United States courts of appeals|United States Court of Appeals]] on September 9, 2010.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/09/10/us/10immig.html Court Rejects a City\u2019s Efforts to Restrict Immigrants], Julia Preston, ''[[The New York Times]]'', September 9, 2010</ref> In a public statement shortly after the decision, Barletta vowed to appeal.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.timesleader.com/news/Federal-appeals-court-affirmsreverses-parts-of-Hazleton-immigration-ordinance.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-06-19 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719172037/http://www.timesleader.com/news/Federal-appeals-court-affirmsreverses-parts-of-Hazleton-immigration-ordinance.html |archivedate=2011-07-19 |df= }}</ref> The Supreme Court declined to hear the case.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.propublica.org/article/kris-kobachs-lucrative-trail-of-courtroom-defeats|title=Kris Kobach\u2019s Lucrative Trail of Courtroom Defeats \u2014 ProPublica|date=2018-08-01|website=ProPublica|language=en-us|others=Jessica Huseman,Blake Paterson,Bryan Lowry,Hunter Woodall|access-date=2018-08-01}}</ref> In 2014, the town of Hazleton was ordered to reimburse the ACLU $1.4 million in legal fees (which was more than one tenth of the annual revenue of the town for 2017), and the town, which was already in debt to the tune of $6 million, had to take additional loans to pay the fees.<ref name=\":4\" /> In 2017, the Pennsylvania Department of Community and Economic Development declared that the town of Hazleton was financially distressed.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n\n====2002====\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania, 2002#District 11|United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania, 2008#District 11|United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania, 2010#District 11|United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania, 2012#District 11}}\n\nIn 2002, Barletta ran as the Republican candidate in the 11th District against nine-term [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] incumbent [[Paul E. Kanjorski|Paul Kanjorski]].  The 11th had long been considered the most Democratic district in Pennsylvania outside of [[Philadelphia]] and [[Pittsburgh]].  However, Barletta was viewed as a very strong candidate\u2014the first credible Republican challenger Kanjorski had faced since his 1986 reelection bid\u2014since he was a very popular Republican mayor from a heavily Democratic city. Barletta lost, taking 42.4% of the vote.  The race might have been much closer had the state legislature not decided to move heavily Democratic [[Scranton]], previously the heart of the 10th District, to the 11th. Barletta lost the district's share of [[Lackawanna County]], home to Scranton, by 32 points; he only trailed in the old 11th by 9,000 votes.<ref name=2002Election>{{cite web|title=2008 Pennsylvania General Election Results |url=http://www.electionreturns.state.pa.us/ElectionsInformation.aspx?FunctionID=13&ElectionID=7&OfficeID=11 |publisher=Pennsylvania Secretary of State, Bureau of Elections, Commissions and Licensure |accessdate=2008-11-01}}</ref>\n\n====2008====\nBarletta faced Kanjorski again in 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.citizensvoice.com/site/news.cfm?newsid=19299089&BRD=2259&PAG=461&dept_id=571464&rfi=6|title=Citizens' Voice|website=www.citizensvoice.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-08-31}}</ref> Lou Barletta denounced the endorsement of  [[David Duke]] in this race.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://timesleader.com/archive/269469/stories-barletta-refuses-kkk-nod107476|title=Barletta refuses KKK nod|last=O'Boyle|first=Bill|date=2008-02-27|work=[[Times Leader]]|access-date=2017-08-31|others=Times Leader|language=en-US}}</ref> Multiple polls had shown Barletta leading Kanjorski by as many as 5 percentage points,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2008/latestpolls/house.html |title=Election 2008 - Latest Polls |publisher=RealClearPolitics |date= |accessdate=2010-08-23}}</ref> and the race has been pegged as one of the nation's most competitive leading into the November elections. That race was one of very few nationwide where a Republican challenger had a credible chance at unseating a Democratic incumbent. Barletta lost to Kanjorski 48%-52%,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.electionreturns.state.pa.us/ElectionsInformation.aspx?FunctionID=13&ElectionID=28&OfficeID=11#11 |title=Commonwealth of PA - Elections Information |publisher=Electionreturns.state.pa.us |date=2008-11-04 |accessdate=2010-08-23 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081208193742/http://www.electionreturns.state.pa.us/ElectionsInformation.aspx?FunctionID=13&ElectionID=28&OfficeID=11 |archivedate=2008-12-08 |df= }}</ref> largely due to losing Lackawanna County by 12,800 votes.  Barletta won the territory that had been in the district prior to the 2000s round of redistricting by almost 4,000 votes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.electionreturns.state.pa.us/ElectionsInformation.aspx?FunctionID=15&ElectionID=28&OfficeID=11&DistrictID=11 |title=Commonwealth of PA - Elections Information |publisher=Electionreturns.state.pa.us |date=2008-11-04 |accessdate=2010-08-23 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120203015641/http://www.electionreturns.state.pa.us/ElectionsInformation.aspx?FunctionID=15&ElectionID=28&OfficeID=11&DistrictID=11 |archivedate=2012-02-03 |df= }}</ref>\n\n====2010====\nBarletta announced on December 9, 2009, that he would once again run for Congress in 2010. He won his party's nomination on Tuesday, May 18, 2010. Barletta won the General Election on November 2, 2010 against Kanjorski by a 55%-45% margin.  City Council President Joe Yannuzzi succeeded Barletta as Mayor of Hazleton on December 15, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|last=Zito |first=Salena |url=http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/opinion/s_673592.html |title=Rust Belt battlegrounds - Pittsburgh Tribune-Review |publisher=Pittsburghlive.com |date=2010-03-28 |accessdate=2010-08-23}}</ref>\n\n====2012====\nBefore the 2012 election, it was widely expected that the state legislature would [[gerrymander]] Barletta's district to make it safer for him. President [[Barack Obama]] carried the old 11th with 57%.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/thefix/mapping-the-future/a-safer-map-for-pennsylvania-r.html | work=The Washington Post | title=Lots at stake for GOP in Pennsylvania redistricting}}</ref>  The new map, as expected, significantly altered the 11th.  Heavily Democratic Scranton and [[Wilkes-Barre]] were shifted to the 17th District.  To make up for the loss of population, the 11th absorbed some heavily Republican territory to the north and south that had previously been in the neighbouring 5th, 10th, 17th and 19th districts, pushing it as far south as the suburbs of [[Harrisburg, Pennsylvania|Harrisburg]].  The new district is approximately ten points more Republican than its predecessor.  Had it existed in 2008, President Obama would have only won 47 percent of the vote here to [[John McCain]]'s 51 percent.<ref>[http://www.dailykos.com/story/2012/11/19/1163009/-Daily-Kos-Elections-presidential-results-by-congressional-district-for-the-2012-2008-elections Presidential results by congressional district] at [[Daily Kos]]</ref> It appeared that the legislature wanted to protect Barletta by packing as many of northeast Pennsylvania's Democratic voters into the 17th as possible.\n\nBarletta won reelection with 58 percent of the vote.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/election/2012/results/state/PA/house/11 |title=U.S. House: Pennsylvania District 11 (Barletta vs Stilp)|work=CNN|accessdate=August 1, 2016|date=December 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\n'''Committee assignments'''\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Homeland Security|Committee on Homeland Security]]'''\n** [[United States House Homeland Security Subcommittee on Border and Maritime Security|Subcommittee on Border and Maritime Security]]\n** [[United States House Homeland Security Subcommittee on Transportation Security|Subcommittee on Transportation Security]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure|Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure]]'''\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Economic Development, Public Buildings and Emergency Management|Subcommittee on Economic Development, Public Buildings, and Emergency Management]] (Chairman)\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Highways and Transit|Subcommittee on Highways and Transit]]\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Railroads, Pipelines, and Hazardous Materials|Subcommittee on Railroads, Pipelines, and Hazardous Materials]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Education and the Workforce|Committee on Education and the Workforce]]'''\n** [[United States House Education Subcommittee on Higher Education and Workforce Training|Subcommittee on Higher Education and Workforce Training]]\n** [[United States House Education Subcommittee on Health, Employment, Labor, and Pensions|Subcommittee on Health, Employment, Labor, and Pensions]]\n\n'''Caucus memberships'''\n* [[Afterschool Caucuses]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=http://www.afterschoolalliance.org/policyCongressionalCaucuses.cfm|format=|publisher=Afterschool Alliance|date=|accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2018 Senate race===\n{{main|United States Senate election in Pennsylvania, 2018}}\nOn July 31, 2017, the Associated Press reported that Barletta was preparing to seek the GOP nomination to challenge [[Bob Casey Jr.|Bob Casey]] for Casey's Senate seat in the [[United States elections, 2018|2018 midterm elections]]. He officially announced on August 29.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/a42c2703411641f9984940ae41d23d70/AP-source:-Barletta-to-seek-US-Senate-seat-held-by-Bob-Casey|title=AP source: Barletta to seek US Senate seat held by Bob Casey|website=AP News|access-date=2017-07-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rollcall.com/news/politics/barletta-announces-his-candidacy-for-senate|title= Barletta Announces His Candidacy for Senate|work=August 29, 2017|accessdate=August 29, 2017}}</ref> He later secured the Republican nomination.<ref>{{cite web|title=2018 Pennsylvania Election Results|accessdate=May 16, 2018|url=https://www.politico.com/election-results/2018/pennsylvania/}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\nAccording to ''Vox'', Barletta is \"considered to be generally more moderate than other House Republicans, though he almost always toes the party line on major votes.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2018/5/15/17355460/lou-barletta-2018-pennsylvania-senate-election|title=Lou Barletta wins Republican nomination in the 2018 Pennsylvania Senate race|work=Vox|accessdate=2018-05-16}}</ref>\n\n===Abortion===\nBarletta voted for [[Pain-Capable Unborn Child Protection Act|Micah's law]],<ref name=\":0\"/> which prohibits abortion of fetuses starting with the twentieth week of pregnancy, when anti-abortion advocates contend that fetuses can be born prematurely with medical assistance and feel pain,<ref>[http://thehill.com/opinion/healthcare/354958-pass-abortion-bill-science-and-basic-human-decency-say-these-babies-are Pass abortion bill \u2014 science and basic human decency say these babies are worth saving] (The Hill)</ref> with exceptions for victims of rape and incest who have undergone counseling and for cases of danger to the life of the mother.<ref>[https://www.congress.gov/bill/115th-congress/house-bill/36 H.R.36 - Pain-Capable Unborn Child Protection Act] (United States Congress)</ref>\n\n===Donald Trump===\nBarletta is a staunch supporter of Donald Trump.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/elections/primaries-set-november-races-pennsylvania-nebraska-oregon-n874536?cid=sm_npd_nn_tw_ma|title=Trump backer wins GOP nod to take on Sen. Casey in Pennsylvania|work=NBC News|accessdate=2018-05-16|language=en-US}}</ref> Barletta endorsed [[Donald Trump]] for president in March 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/2016-gop-primary-live-updates-and-results/2016/03/lou-barletta-endorses-donald-trump-221099|title=Rep. Lou Barletta endorses Trump, hopes others will too|last1=Collins|first1=Eliza|date=March 22, 2016|accessdate=9 October 2016|publisher=Politico}}</ref> According to ''NBC News'', \"Barletta is a favorite of Trump... Trump asked Barletta to run for Senate.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> Barletta was reportedly considered for a position in the Trump administration.<ref name=\":0\" /> In his 2018 Senate campaign, Barletta pledged to \"give President Trump the help he needs\".<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\n===Economy and budget===\nOn April 15, 2011, Barletta voted with the Republican majority for [[Paul Ryan]]'s budget. Barletta has characterized a [[balanced budget amendment]] as a gimmick and said he will not vote to raise the debt ceiling.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://standardspeaker.com/news/barletta-discusses-stance-on-budget-matters-1.1135926?localLinksEnabled=false|title=Barletta discusses stance on budget matters|author=Tom Ragan|date=22 April 2011|publisher=The Standard Speaker|accessdate=25 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Barletta voted for the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017|Tax Cuts and Jobs Act]], the Republican Party's tax reform legislation.<ref name=\":0\"/> In supporting the legislation, Barletta tweeted, \"Our #TaxReform package doubles standard deduction, brings $$$ back home, and reduces rates for ALL taxpayers. We will #MAGA.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.politifact.com/pennsylvania/statements/2017/dec/06/lou-barletta/pa-rep-lou-barletta-overstates-benefits-house-tax-/|title=PA Rep. Lou Barletta overstates benefits of the House tax bi|work=@politifact|accessdate=2018-05-16|language=en}}</ref> According to [[PolitiFact]], Barletta's claim is \"mostly false\", as the tax plan in 2018 cuts taxes for approximately 75% of Americans, while increasing them on 7%; by 2027, the tax plan will raise taxes for more than 25% of Americans.<ref name=\":2\"/>\n\n===Healthcare===\nOn January 31, 2014, Barletta introduced the [[Protecting Volunteer Firefighters and Emergency Responders Act (H.R. 3979; 113th Congress)]] into the House.<ref name=\"3979sum\">{{cite web|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/3979|title=H.R. 3979 - Summary|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=10 March 2014}}</ref> The bill would amend the [[Internal Revenue Code]] to exclude volunteer hours of volunteer firefighters and emergency medical personnel from counting towards the calculation of the number of a firm's full-time employees for purposes of certain provisions of the [[Affordable Care Act]].<ref name=\"3979cbo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cbo.gov/publication/45103|title=H.R. 3979 - CBO|publisher=Congressional Budget Office|accessdate=10 March 2014}}</ref> This mean that there was no requirement that volunteer emergency responders be offered health care by the organization they volunteer with.<ref name=\"PeteGOPeyes\">{{cite news|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/200316-gop-hoping-dems-help-expand-obamacare-exemptions|title=GOP eyes Dem help on ObamaCare|last=Kasperowicz|first=Pete|date=10 March 2014|newspaper=The Hill|accessdate=11 March 2014}}</ref> Barletta argued that the bill was necessary because the [[Internal Revenue Service]] had initially said that it would be requiring organizations to provide these volunteers with insurance, something that would be prohibitively expensive for some of them.<ref name=\"PeteGOPeyes\"/>\n\nBarletta voted for House legislation to repeal the Affordable Care Act (Obamacare).<ref name=\":0\"/> Barletta had threatened not to support Obamacare repeal because he wanted the repeal legislation to prohibit undocumented immigrants from applying for health insurance tax credits.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.mcall.com/news/nationworld/pennsylvania/capitol-ideas/mc-lou-barletta-opposes-gop-obamacare-repeal-bill-20170321-story.html|title=Lou Barletta opposes GOP Obamacare repeal bill|last=Olson|first=Laura|work=themorningcall.com|accessdate=2018-05-16|language=en-US}}</ref> After meeting with President Trump and House Speaker Paul Ryan, Barletta said that they had promised to bring up separate legislation to prohibit undocumented immigrants from accessing health insurance tax credits.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.mcall.com/news/nationworld/pennsylvania/capitol-ideas/mc-lou-barletta-switches-to-a-yes-on-obamacare-repeal-bill-20170322-story.html|title=Lou Barletta switches to a 'yes' on Obamacare repeal bill|last=Olson|first=Laura|work=themorningcall.com|accessdate=2018-05-16|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===Immigration===\nBarletta supports President [[Donald Trump]]'s 2017 [[Executive Order 13769|executive order]] imposing a ban on entry to the U.S. to citizens of seven Muslim-majority countries, saying: \"I commend President Trump for suspending the refugee program, and in particular for Syria and the six other countries, because they are unquestionably terrorist havens and hotspots.\"<ref name=\"Blake1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2017/01/29/heres-where-republicans-stand-on-president-trumps-controversial-travel-ban/|title=Whip Count: Here's where Republicans stand on Trump's controversial travel ban|last1=Blake|first1=Aaron|date=January 31, 2017|work=Washington Post}}</ref> In 2007, Barletta opposed [[Comprehensive Immigration Reform Act of 2007|comprehensive immigration reform]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/01/25/politics/kfile-lou-barletta-american-free-press/index.html|title=GOP Senate candidate Lou Barletta did interview in 2006 with Holocaust-denying publication|last=CNN|first=Andrew Kaczynski and Chris Massie,|work=CNN|accessdate=2018-05-16}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, CNN reported that Barletta had been associated with a number of fringe anti-immigration groups and organizations.<ref name=\":3\"/> In 2006, he gave an interview to American Free Press, an outlet that said that 9/11 was a \"Jewish plot\" and denies the Holocaust.<ref name=\":3\"/> In 2007, Barletta appeared with American Free Press' \"roving editor\" Mark Anderson, a Bilderberg conspiracy theorist and Holocaust denier, at a Hazleton rally in support of Anderson.<ref name=\":3\"/> At the rally, Barletta said that the Comprehensive Immigration Reform Act of 2007 that the Bush administration was pursuing, would reward some immigrants who are \"murders, rapists, thieves, and terrorists\" with legal status.<ref name=\":3\"/> In 2007, Barletta gave an interview to Americans for Immigration Control, which believes the \"annual tidal wave of over a million immigrants (legal and illegal) is endangering our American way of life.\"<ref name=\":3\"/> In 2011, Barletta spoke at an event hosted by the anti-Muslim journal The Social Contract, whose editor is a white nationalist.<ref name=\":3\" /> In 2011, he appeared at an event hosted by the ultra-conservative student group Youth for Western Civilization, which opposes \"radical multiculturalism, political correctness, racial preferences, mass immigration, and socialism.\"<ref name=\":3\"/>\n\nWhen asked whether Barletta had known of the views of the people and groups mentioned in the CNN story at the time he associated with them, Barletta spokesperson Jon Anzur responded that Barletta had \"always condemned 'hate, bigotry, and racial supremacy in all its forms.'\" Anzur added, \"'Of course Lou was not aware of these individuals\u2019 background[s]\u2026.As the mayor of a small city, Lou didn't have the resources or staff to screen everyone who asked him questions\u2026 Lou did 27 interviews [one day], from World News Tonight to Tucker Carlson. Lou had one assistant, not a team of consultants\u2026'\"<ref name=\":3\"/> Anzur also noted that Barletta stated that a New Jersey Ku Klux Klan organization that wanted to demonstrate in Hazleton in 2007 was not welcome, and that Barletta had renounced a 2008 endorsement he had received from former Ku Klux Klan leader David Duke in 2008.<ref name=\":3\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{commonscat}}\n* [http://barletta.house.gov/ Congressman Lou Barletta] official U.S. House site\n* [http://loubarletta.com/ Lou Barletta for Congress]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Pennsylvania/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Lou_Barletta_%5BR-11%5D}}\n* {